### Top 5 skills to make this project better (not already mentioned)

*   **playwright-cli-ms (E2E + flow reliability)**
    Why it helps here: your plan has multi-step flows (diagnostic → transitions → module 2 → score; drill sessions; simulation timers). Playwright E2E tests catch regressions in routing, timing UI, “Submit Module” enable/disable logic, and module transitions.
    Best target tests:
    /diagnostic happy path through Module 1 → Module 2 → results
    timer expiry auto-submit
    “flag for review” / navigation constraints (if implemented)
    /analytics empty state vs populated state
*   **frontend-design (UI polish for simulation/analytics screens)**
    Why it helps here: Simulation UX and analytics dashboards are “feel” features. This skill is good for making the UI production-grade (layout, typography, information hierarchy) so it doesn’t look like component shells.
    Best use spots:
    analytics route layout (SkillBreakdown + ProgressChart + WeaknessList)
    module header (timer + question nav + submit)
    module transition screen and results pages
*   **schema-markup (structured data for SEO + rich results)**
    Why it helps here: you’re planning public-facing pages and likely FAQs/how-it-works pages. Schema boosts eligibility for rich results and improves how pages are understood.
    Most relevant schema types:
    FAQPage (FAQ sections)
    Organization / WebSite
    Product (if there’s pricing/subscription)
    BreadcrumbList (if you add subpages)
*   **seo-audit (catch technical/on-page SEO issues early)**
    Why it helps here: the plan calls for SEO work on subpages; an audit skill helps ensure routing/indexability, metadata, canonical tags, sitemap/robots, performance basics, and duplicate title/descriptions don’t quietly sabotage it.
    Especially important if you’re using client-side routing: you’ll want to be intentional about SSR/prerendering and metadata management.
*   **programmatic-seo (scale SAT keyword pages from the content taxonomy)**
    Why it helps here: your content model naturally maps to many pages:
    question types, skills, trap types, domains, difficulty bands
    “Skill: X” landing pages + practice sets + explanations
    This skill complements your content pipeline: once bulk import is working, you can generate a directory of SEO pages programmatically.